## Do you have some experience with programming? Pick one of these…

*All of the following lessons use the <a href=“https://youtu.be/-EoTeD4mSNU” target=_blank>Design Mode</a> feature of App Lab. During your in-person workshop in November or December you will have a chance to learn more about design mode, but make sure you spend time with <a href = “https://studio.code.org/s/cspunit3/lessons/12/levels/1” target=_blank>Lesson 12</a> if you want more background and support with design mode!*


### Lessons 14 - 15: Variables

**Consider doing if:** You want to learn about the mental model for variables, and how variables in computer science are different than variables in math (covered in lesson 14) **OR** if you want to learn how to use variables in a JavaScript game (lesson 15).

**Lesson Plans:** <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1viYBN86bIVM-LiAMKu4uiQzTzKPn8LFNw5AvCg0MoxU/edit" target =_blank>Lesson 14: Controlling Memory with Variables >></a> |
<a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lnMZkS6e9Ws2U4Tu3Kb_JQEgUNQMS8rFxv7HaU3Ujvg/edit" target =_blank > Lesson 15: Using Variables in Apps >></a>

>**You will learn:** These lessons introduce the idea of controlling the computer's memory with variables. global variables (and scope), basic if-statements updating global variables in response to events (keeping score, etc.)

>**You will produce:** A simple clicker game that keeps track of score and lives in variables. The program will use a basic if-statement to determine if the player is won or lost.

>**You will share:** The program you create on <a href="https://studio.code.org/s/cspunit3/lessons/15/levels/21" target=_blank> Stage 15, level 21.</a>

### Lesson 16: Strings

**Consider doing if:** You want to learn how to manipulate strings of text in JavaScript and App Lab.

**Lesson Plans:** <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1IO9PLhK4vIHAWHwSbeBYPeQbXuxbfgkG14AVCjksgaE/edit" target =_blank>Lesson 16: User Inputs and Strings >></a>

>**You will learn:** How to collect text that has been input by a user, and how to join together (or concatenate) strings.

>**You will produce:** A Mad Libs style fill-in-the-blank game.

>**You will share:** The program you create on <a href="https://studio.code.org/s/cspunit3/lessons/16/levels/14" target=_blank>Stage 16, level 14.</a>

### Lessons 18: Programming Flow and Conditionals

**Consider doing if:** You want to learn more about programming with conditionals, and understanding the role of if-statements in an event-driven programming world. 

**Lesson Plans:** <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1th8qtPnVU0_60WVIgZ3XhaAbFiyqpmNvL1-2sBQt2M0/edit" target =_blank>Lesson 18: Programmig Flow and Logic >></a>

>**You will learn:** About the different ways to combine if- and else- statements to control the flow of the program.

>**You will produce:** a guessing game where the user tries to guess a secret number and they recieve feedback on if their guess is high or low.

>**You will share:** The program you create on <a href="https://studio.code.org/s/cspunit3/lessons/18/levels/12" target=_blank>Stage 18, level 12.</a>
